In this Ode, as in a. 19. Horace has tried to catch the inspiration oi a Greek dithyramb. In that one he professes to recall the effects which the sight ot Bacchus had upon him: in the present one he is actually under the infinence ot the afflatus. ‘He is hurried away, whither he knows not: his eyes are opened on strange caverna and river-hanla and woods. His tongue will be loosed ina moment to sing no humble theme, and in no common strain, the glories os Caesar: he follows the god, sor he must, and it is delightiul, but it is seariul too!
